 of False Accusations and Persecutions -- tChapter 15: Shackling, Attacking, and Oppressing the People -- tChapter 16: Lin Biao’s Rein on the Armed Forces -- tChapter 17: The Lushan Conference [1970] -- tChapter 18: The United Flotilla and the 5–7–1 Project -- tChapter 19: The Failure of the Lin Biao Coup -- tChapter 20: The September 13 Incident and Death of Lin Biao -- tPART THREE: Jiang Qing and the Politics of the Cultural Revolution -- tChapter 21: New Life Created by the Cultural Revolution -- tChapter 22: Special Cases, Forced Confessions, Fabricated Proof -- tChapter 23: Erasing the Stains of the 1930s -- tChapter 24: Escalation of Armed Struggle -- tChapter 25: Arts Criticism and the “Revolution of Beijing Opera” -- tChapter 26: The September 13 Incident and the “Trough” -- tChapter 27: “Criticize Lin Biao, Confucius, and the Duke of Zhou” -- tChapter 28: Deng Xiaoping’s Overall Rectification -- tChapter 29: The Tiananmen Square Incident [1976] -- tChapter 30: The Downfall of the Gang of Four -- tConcluding Remarks -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tSelected Further Readings -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYan Jiaqi, one of the principal leaders of China's pro-democracy movement, and his wife, Gao Gao, a noted sociologist, set out to write a comprehensive narrative account of the Great Proletariat Cultural Revolution, which occurred in the second decade after Mao Zedong and his comrades came to power. It appeared in Hong Kong in 1986, and was quickly banned by the Communist government. Not surprisingly, censorship and restricted circulation in China resulted in underground reproduction and serialization. The work was thus widely read, coveted, and appreciated by a populace who had just freed itself from the cultural drought and political dread of the event. Yan and Gao later spent two years revising and expanding their work. The present volume, Turbulent Decade: A History of the Cultural Revolution, is based on the revised edition and has been masterfully edited and translated by D.W.Y. Kwok in consultation with the authors. It makes available for the first time in English Yan and Gao's remarkable record of the traumatic Cultural Revolution decade and remains the only single-volume narrative history of the revolution written from an independent and personal perspective. It is a sweeping historical account, notable for its moral courage, for its empathy, for the significance of the questions it addresses, and for its sobering, ultimately tragic view of human behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aGao, Gao, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGao, Gao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiaqi, Yan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwok, Daniel W. Y., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486531340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824865313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824865313.jpg  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK